    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section>
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Creatine Gummies</h2>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Do creatine gummies work as well as creatine powder?</summary>
        <p>Yes. Creatine gummies that deliver the clinically studied dose of 3-5 grams of creatine monohydrate per day are equally effective as powder. The form of delivery does not change how creatine is absorbed by your body. The key factor is total daily dose, not whether it comes as a gummy, capsule, or powder. The primary advantage of gummies is compliance: if you are more likely to take a gummy consistently every day, the gummy form may actually be more effective for you in practice.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>How many grams of creatine per day do I need?</summary>
        <p>The International Society of Sports Nutrition (ISSN) recommends 3-5 grams of creatine monohydrate per day for maintenance. Most clinical studies showing benefits for strength, power, and muscle mass use a 5g daily dose. Some products on our list offer only 2-4g, which may still provide benefits but falls below the most-studied dosage. For most adults weighing 150 lbs or more, 5g per day is the recommended target.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Are creatine gummies safe?</summary>
        <p>Creatine monohydrate is one of the most studied supplements in sports nutrition history, with over 500 peer-reviewed studies confirming its safety and efficacy. Creatine gummies are generally recognized as safe when taken at recommended doses. Look for products with third-party testing from NSF, Informed Sport, or USP to ensure purity and accurate labeling. Individuals with pre-existing kidney conditions should consult a healthcare provider before starting creatine supplementation.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Do creatine gummies cause bloating?</summary>
        <p>Creatine can cause temporary water retention in muscle cells, which some people perceive as bloating. This effect is more common during a loading phase (20g/day for 5-7 days). At a standard maintenance dose of 3-5g per day, most users experience minimal to no bloating. Creatine HCl variants claim to reduce this effect, though the peer-reviewed evidence for this claim is limited and most research uses monohydrate at the full 5g dose. Staying well-hydrated typically minimizes any water retention.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>When is the best time to take creatine gummies?</summary>
        <p>Timing is less important than consistency. Research shows that taking creatine at any time of day is effective as long as you take it daily. Some studies suggest a slight advantage to taking creatine post-workout with a carbohydrate source for enhanced uptake, but the difference is marginal. The single most important factor for creatine effectiveness is daily adherence over weeks and months, not timing.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Are creatine gummies worth the extra cost over powder?</summary>
        <p>Creatine gummies cost $0.67-$1.17 per serving compared to roughly $0.05-$0.15 per serving for creatine monohydrate powder. The premium is significant, often 10-20x more expensive. However, if convenience and taste help you take creatine consistently every single day, the extra cost may be justified. Consistency is the most important factor in creatine effectiveness. A $1.00 gummy you actually take daily outperforms a $0.05 powder that sits in your cabinet.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Can women take creatine gummies?</summary>
        <p>Absolutely. Creatine is equally safe and effective for women. Peer-reviewed research shows creatine supplementation supports lean muscle retention, bone mineral density, cognitive function, and exercise performance in women. Brands like Arrae specifically formulate and market creatine gummies for female athletes and active women — and unlike many female-targeted products, Arrae delivers the full 5g clinical dose rather than cutting to 2-4g. There is no physiological reason for women to avoid creatine. The outdated concern about "bulking up" is not supported by the scientific literature.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Do I need to do a loading phase with creatine gummies?</summary>
        <p>A loading phase (20g/day for 5-7 days) saturates muscles faster but is not required. Taking 3-5g daily will fully saturate your creatine stores within 3-4 weeks and produce the same long-term results. Given that creatine gummies are more expensive per gram than powder, skipping the loading phase and simply taking the daily maintenance dose is the more practical and cost-effective approach. You will reach full saturation either way.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

